ura</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Abramovsky</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE017231%2F1"><gtr:id>5C4F553D-7645-4616-9C89-BCEC49616F6B</gtr:id><gtr:title>Investigating business-university innovation linkages</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E017231/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This research will provide comprehensive evidence for Great Britain on linkages between university research departments and private sector innovation activity. The project will address two research questions.&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>First, it will investigate whether firms locate their research and development (R&amp;amp;D) facilities near to university research departments and whether the quality of university research matters for the extent of geographic clustering. For example, do firms in the pharmaceuticals industry locate their R&amp;amp;D laboratories near to chemistry and medical science departments carrying out world-class frontier research? Evidence that they do might imply that close geographic proximity to universities enables firms to capitalise better on the expertise of university scientists. &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The research will also look at the geographic clustering of foreign-owned R&amp;amp;D labs around universities within Great Britain. Evidence that foreign-owned firms locate in the vicinity of frontier research departments would be in line with firms sourcing technology from Higher Education Institutions internationally.&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The second research question examines university-business interactions more directly. It will investigate whether geographic proximity to university research departments of varying research quality is related to the likelihood that firms engage in co-operative R&amp;amp;D arrangements with universities and use information and knowledge generated by universities to help them innovate.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-04-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-05-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>43936</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Geographic proximity and firm-university innovation linkages: evidence from Great Britain, Conference</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>4C24B25F-31B8-43D9-9CD5-2681E3A55E7C</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Discussion with policy makers

